==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|æcern||lang=ang}}, from {{term|æcer||lang=ang|field, acre}} (Modern English {{term|acre|lang=en}}); akin to Dutch {{term|aker|lang=nl}}, German ''[[ecker]]'', Icelandic ''[[akarn]]'', Danish ''[[agern]]'', Gothic {{term|𐌰𐌺𐍂𐌰𐌽|tr=akran||fruit|lang=got}}, {{term|𐌰𐌺𐍂𐍃|tr=akrs||field|lang=got}}; — originally "fruit of the field". See [[acre]]. Spelling influenced by {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|ac|lang=ang||oak}} and {{term|corn||grain|lang=ang}}

